00:34:04.860 --> 00:34:08.409
do we got?
We're good? All right.

00:34:08.409 --> 00:34:13.450
Till the beer's gone -- that's when the thing
ends, right?

00:34:13.450 --> 00:34:17.809
Basically, first of all, all of our bottled
beers go through a process called 'bottled

00:34:17.809 --> 00:34:21.369
conditioning'.
And it's a process that's traditional in the

00:34:21.369 --> 00:34:24.279
traditional breweries in Belgium.
Not all Belgium brewers do it.

00:34:24.279 --> 00:34:28.530
And very few breweries in the U.S. do it.
And basically what that process -- the beer

00:34:28.530 --> 00:34:34.349
gets bottled with a little or no carbonation.
And just prior to bottling it -- just like

00:34:34.349 --> 00:34:39.129
the champagne makers do -- we'll add a fresh
dose of yeast and sugar to the beer, mix it

00:34:39.129 --> 00:34:42.569
up, and then bottle it.
And then the beer goes into our warm room

00:34:42.569 --> 00:34:46.269
 -- or our cellar -- and there's a secondary
fermentation of the bottle.

00:34:46.269 --> 00:34:51.269
The yeast will eat the sugar, give off carbon
dioxide and alcohol, and that process can

00:34:51.269 --> 00:34:57.059
take a week to a few months depending on the
beer, but it naturally carbonates the beer.

00:34:57.059 --> 00:35:00.880
So that's why these beers all have a yeast
sediment in the bottom of them.

00:35:00.880 --> 00:35:07.930
But that process gives you a huge amount of
additional layers of flavor and aromas and

00:35:07.930 --> 00:35:10.559
complexity.
And it also increases the shelf life of the

00:35:10.559 --> 00:35:14.829
beer by quite a bit.
So the basic run down of the white.

00:35:14.829 --> 00:35:21.630
I mentioned traditional Belgian style wheat
beer -- five percent unfiltered and spiced.

00:35:21.630 --> 00:35:30.369
The double and triple are the Trappist style
beers we brew, which I described those.

00:35:30.369 --> 00:35:36.529
The next would be the Curieux, which is our
triple age in the Jim Beam bourbon barrels.

00:35:36.529 --> 00:35:37.880
And then, a couple beers we haven't tried
yet.

00:35:37.880 --> 00:35:41.539
I think the only other two are the Odyssey
and the Black.

00:35:41.539 --> 00:35:47.450
The Odyssey is an interesting one. We brewed
that.

00:35:47.450 --> 00:35:52.630
And we have a real open culture at the brewery.
If anyone has an idea on a beer, we're open

00:35:52.630 --> 00:35:55.920
to listening to it.
It's not just me -- in fact, I didn't come

00:35:55.920 --> 00:35:58.900
up with most of these beers.
It's usually someone at the brewery that has

00:35:58.900 --> 00:36:02.959
a cool idea for a cool beer.
And we'll all kind of look at each other and

00:36:02.959 --> 00:36:05.799
be like, "Yeah, let's try it.
Let's try brewing it."

00:36:05.799 --> 00:36:08.870
So, you know, anyone -- even if they work
in the office -- they can come up with an

00:36:08.870 --> 00:36:12.260
idea for a beer.
And nowadays -- I mean, we used to just brew

00:36:12.260 --> 00:36:14.650
it and dry it.
Nowadays, we'll be a little more methodical

00:36:14.650 --> 00:36:19.640
and do it on a small scale, but.
A guy named Scott Abel came up with this recipe.

00:36:19.640 --> 00:36:27.619
And it's a dark wheat beer.
And it's very unlike most wheat beers that

00:36:27.619 --> 00:36:31.289
you usually think of as traditional wheat
beers.

00:36:31.289 --> 00:36:35.579
A lot of roasted malts.
When we fermented it out the first time, it

00:36:35.579 --> 00:36:39.519
really didn't have a whole lot of character.
It was kind of thin and dry.

00:36:39.519 --> 00:36:45.640
But we liked where the beer was going, so
we decided to take a small portion of it and

00:36:45.640 --> 00:36:50.960
age it in new American oak barrels.
Kind of give it a real like vanilla, mocha

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:54.180
character.
So we took about 25, 30 percent of the beer,

00:36:54.180 --> 00:36:59.450
got some new American oak barrels -- the same
ones they'd used if you were aging a wine

00:36:59.450 --> 00:37:05.799
in an American oak barrel -- and aged the
beer for ten months in the oak, aged the remainder

00:37:05.799 --> 00:37:09.769
of the beer for ten months in stainless steel,
and then blended the two together.

00:37:09.769 --> 00:37:18.289
And again, just between the time in that oak,
it totally transforms the beer.

00:37:18.289 --> 00:37:22.369
You can get a big vanilla character in this
beer.

00:37:22.369 --> 00:37:27.049
This particular batch has got almost a little
bit of a smoky character to it and mocha.

00:37:27.049 --> 00:37:31.219
That's all from the medium and light toast
oak barrels.

00:37:31.219 --> 00:37:38.670
Something else I going to mention about this
beer but I forgot, so.

00:37:38.670 --> 00:37:42.890
It's interesting -- with the barrels, a lot
of people say, you know, "Why do you age in

00:37:42.890 --> 00:37:44.819
barrels?
Is that just kind of marketing or gimmicky?

00:37:44.819 --> 00:37:49.579
Does it really do anything to the beer?" And
the answer is, "It absolutely transforms the

00:37:49.579 --> 00:37:52.120
beer.
It becomes a totally different beer."

00:37:52.120 --> 00:38:03.890
If you were to take this same base beer -- age
the same beer in a bourbon barrel, a wine

00:38:03.890 --> 00:38:09.150
barrel that's been used for wine, a new American
oak barrel, a new French oak barrel, you get

00:38:09.150 --> 00:38:12.570
totally different beers out of those barrels
after a few months.

00:38:12.570 --> 00:38:13.690
Q [inaudible]

00:38:13.690 --> 00:38:18.509
Rob Tod: Absolutely yeah. Yeah.
It picks up tons of flavors of vanillans from

00:38:18.509 --> 00:38:23.589
the wood, tannens from the wood, a number
of flavors.

00:38:23.589 --> 00:38:30.959
And actually, and we use this with the Interlude.
A lot of these microbes, bacterias, and wild

00:38:30.959 --> 00:38:34.599
yeast can actually live in the wood.
The wood can support them.

00:38:34.599 --> 00:38:38.680
So you can empty a barrel, and those microbes
will stay in it.

00:38:38.680 --> 00:38:42.510
And then add another batch of beer, age it
for six months to a year, and those microbes

00:38:42.510 --> 00:38:47.469
will start working away at that beer, transforming
it, giving you some nice tart characters,

00:38:47.469 --> 00:38:49.839
funky characters. So.

