00:48:57.199 --> 00:49:02.109
It was like a perfect storm.
For years, hop prices have been depressed.

00:49:02.109 --> 00:49:05.180
Farmers weren't making money on it.
They were pulling their crops.

00:49:05.180 --> 00:49:09.670
And it takes a couple years for a hop crop
to really establish itself.

00:49:09.670 --> 00:49:14.519
So, they were pulling it out, and basically
supply was starting to go down, and it got

00:49:14.519 --> 00:49:19.369
to the point where supply dipped right down
to where demand was.

00:49:19.369 --> 00:49:24.229
And at the same time that happened, there
was a big warehouse fire.

00:49:24.229 --> 00:49:27.670
A bunch of hops burned in a warehouse -- couple
percent of the supply.

00:49:27.670 --> 00:49:32.459
There was a spidermite infestation in the
Pacific Northwest.

00:49:32.459 --> 00:49:36.229
And there's hailstorms in Germany that destroyed
crops.

00:49:36.229 --> 00:49:39.380
So all this stuff happened at once.
And there was a panic.

00:49:39.380 --> 00:49:42.700
Hops is one of those things that there's a
little bit of extra hops in the market, the

00:49:42.700 --> 00:49:47.650
