00:53:17.579 --> 00:53:25.150
And we really focused on visiting lambic breweries.
When I was over there, I got all excited about

00:53:25.150 --> 00:53:28.459
lambic beers.
And then, towards the end of the trip, I was

00:53:28.459 --> 00:53:30.930
like, "You know what?
These are really -- let's leave these to the

00:53:30.930 --> 00:53:35.109
Belgians."
These beers -- basically, what you do with

00:53:35.109 --> 00:53:40.369
these beers is, you brew a batch of beer,
and instead of cooling it after the brewing

00:53:40.369 --> 00:53:46.069
process, after the boil, in a sterile heat
exchanger and adding a single-cell yeast culture

00:53:46.069 --> 00:53:51.309
and fermenting the beer out with this controlled
yeast culture, you cool the beer in a big

00:53:51.309 --> 00:53:56.989
open vessel exposed to the outside air.
The outside air both cools the beer and it

00:53:56.989 --> 00:54:01.519
also adds natural yeast and bacteria to the
beer.

00:54:01.519 --> 00:54:06.289
And basically, all brewers -- really, in the
world -- have always been told that you can

00:54:06.289 --> 00:54:11.760
only really make these traditional lambic
beers in the Zenne Valley region in the Brussels

00:54:11.760 --> 00:54:17.720
area -- in Belgium.
So, I just woke up one morning about a year

00:54:17.720 --> 00:54:21.059
after going on that trip, and I was just like,
"Let's just try making these beers. Why not?"

00:54:21.059 --> 00:54:27.160
So, it'll probably be a huge waste of money,
but you can see -- we built -- this is a koelschip

00:54:27.160 --> 00:54:34.589
that we built on the slide here.
This holds about 400 gallons of beer.

00:54:34.589 --> 00:54:41.289
The boiled wort goes into this vessel, cools
overnight, gets inoculated with natural yeast

00:54:41.289 --> 00:54:44.819
and bacteria from Portland.
We had no idea whether this would work.

00:54:44.819 --> 00:54:47.019
We didn't do any kind of experimentation.
We just did it.

00:54:47.019 --> 00:54:51.100
It was kind of stupid. [laughter]
But we were curious to see if it would work.

00:54:51.100 --> 00:54:58.349
And it actually did work.
The beer -- you can see this is the wort being

00:54:58.349 --> 00:55:03.329
pumped into this room.
The louvered windows let the air in.

00:55:03.329 --> 00:55:06.509
I don't know if we'll ever sell this beer.
We were more just curious to see if it would

00:55:06.509 --> 00:55:07.509
work.

00:55:07.509 --> 00:55:08.509
Q [inaudible]

00:55:08.509 --> 00:55:13.049
Rob Tod: No. No breweries outside of Belgium
really do it.

00:55:13.049 --> 00:55:18.599
